Excellent! Now I can see the full picture:

1. In the current version of SymPy (1.14.0), a handler has been added at line 142-144:
```python
@is_subset_sets.register(ProductSet, FiniteSet)
def _(a_ps, b_fs):
    return fuzzy_and(b_fs.contains(x) for x in a_ps)
```

This is exactly the fix that was needed! When `ProductSet.is_subset(FiniteSet)` is called, it now iterates over all elements of the `ProductSet` and checks if each is contained in the `FiniteSet`.


2. There's also a method on `FiniteSet` that handles the reverse case - when checking if a `FiniteSet` is a subset of anything else, it verifies that each element of the `FiniteSet` is contained in the other set. So the bug has been fixed in version 1.14.0, likely addressing an issue from around 2019-2020 when SymPy was at version 1.4-1.5.

Now I need to look at the relational.py file to understand why `Eq(b, c).simplify()` is crashing with an `AttributeError` about `Complement` objects missing an `equals` method.
